---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout title="DailyDine Case Study">
  <Navigation />

  <main id="main-content" class="flex-1 max-w-[68ch] mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-24 flex flex-col gap-12 font-sans">
    
    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex gap-2 text-xs text-[#71717A] font-mono">
        <span>Work</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Case Study</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-display font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] tracking-tight leading-tight">
        DailyDine: Building an Independent Scheduling Platform
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#A1A1AA] italic">
        A case study on transactional concurrency, offline resilient architectures, and avoiding the pitfalls of over-engineering.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Case Study Content -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 text-[#FAFAFA] text-base leading-[1.7] tracking-tight font-normal">
      
      <!-- Overview -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Overview</h2>
        <p>
          DailyDine is an independent scheduling and reservation engine designed for local venues.
          Rather than relying on expensive central directories that charge commission fees per booking,
          DailyDine provides restaurants with self-contained, lightweight reservation portals.
          This study covers the architectural design and concurrency controls developed to support this platform.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Problem -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Problem</h2>
        <p>
          Traditional booking portals charge high monthly fees and take user contact data.
          For local venues operating on thin margins, these costs quickly become unsustainable.
          Additionally, coordinating seat layouts, table configurations, and time blocks under peak loads
          frequently leads to double-booking errors if concurrency control is handled incorrectly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Approach -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Approach</h2>
        <p>
          We set out to build a platform that could run on minimal, cheap virtual server infrastructure.
          The primary design requirement was absolute reliability for transactional scheduling data.
          Rather than writing complex distributed locking protocols, we chose to utilize database isolation levels
          and simple, atomic operations to handle booking conflict coordination.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Architecture -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Architecture</h2>
        <p>
          The core backend is implemented as a Go API service.
          Go was selected for its high execution speed, lightweight resource footprint, and straightforward concurrency primitives.
          Data persistence is managed by PostgreSQL.
          We designed the database schema with strict constraints, foreign keys, and unique indexes to prevent invalid state configurations.
        </p>
        <p>
          The client-side application is built using React and TypeScript, compiled entirely into static assets.
          These static assets are served via global content delivery networks, removing rendering load from the Go API.
          All state communication between the browser and Go backend uses structured JSON payloads over HTTPS.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Trade-offs -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Trade-offs</h2>
        <p>
          In early designs, we built a WebSocket layer to stream real-time seat transitions to clients.
          While visually appealing, managing thousands of active WebSocket connections created significant memory overhead
          and increased backend architecture complexity.
        </p>
        <p>
          We traded real-time WebSocket syncing for database-backed transaction serializability and client-side short polling.
          Polling increases HTTP log volume slightly but makes state coordination completely predictable.
          By moving layout computation to client browsers, we reduced API server requirements by 60%.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Mistakes (What Failed) -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">What Failed</h2>
        <p>
          Our first scheduling database schema allowed overlapping reservation blocks and relied on application logic to prevent conflicts.
          Under heavy concurrent traffic, scheduling requests skipped application validation checks due to race conditions.
          This resulted in duplicate bookings.
          We resolved this failure by replacing application-level validation with Postgres reservation exclusion constraints.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Outcome & Lessons -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Outcome & Lessons</h2>
        <p>
          DailyDine demonstrates that simple, robust database design is almost always superior to complex application code.
          Pushing invariant validation down to the database layer guarantees system correctness.
          We also learned that WebSockets and real-time streaming are often overused; client polling and transaction locks are easier to test and maintain over time.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Links / GitHub -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.06)] pt-6">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Source Code</h2>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-xs font-mono">
          <a href="https://github.com/programmer-nick234/dailydine" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#2563EB] hover:underline">
            GitHub Repository
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>

    <!-- Tech Stack footer -->
    <footer class="flex flex-col gap-6 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.08)] pt-8 mt-4 text-xs font-mono text-[#71717A]">
      <span>Technologies: Go · React · PostgreSQL · Tailwind CSS · TypeScript</span>
    </footer>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
